b'On  Friday, 6/19, our offices and banking centers will close at 2 p.m. local time in observance of Juneteenth. As an organization we plan to pause, reflect, and contemplate its significance and what it meant 155 years ago, what it means today, and how we might take action to make tomorrow better for everyone. While it is only one small step toward a more racially just and equitable organization and community, we believe it is a step in the right direction.'

b'#TBT during Women\xe2\x80\x99s History Month: Sophie Hamant, a Fifth-Third National employee, began her career selling Liberty Bonds during WWI. Later, she was 1 of 6 women in the U.S. to head a foreign exchange department. Over 130 companies depended on Sophie for daily exchange rates.'

b'#TBT in celebration of Women\xe2\x80\x99s History Month. Many women have made history at Fifth Third including Miriam Nagel. She became the first female bank officer in 1961 when very few women in banking held the title. Today, Fifth Third has 3,000+ women officers. Equality is a #53Better.'

b"#TBT: Teller's cages were a staple of early 20th century bank architecture, offering tellers and the bank's assets additional security. This photo from Fifth National dates back to 1914. Fifth Third was one of the first banks in Cincinnati to remove teller\xe2\x80\x99s cages in 1932."
